  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Glory.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—Perhaps, properly, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the glory",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e.,",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the divine glory: that pre-eminent glory with which no other can compare.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If this is the case, then it would be better to supply “is” than “be.” His own peculiar glory does belong to God, and therefore the Christian ascribes it to Him as that which is already His; he does not pray for it as something unfulfilled, as, e.g., he prays for the coming of God’s kingdom.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "If this is the case, then it would be better to supply “is” than “be.” His own peculiar glory ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "does",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " belong to God, and therefore the Christian ascribes it to Him as that which is already His; he does not pray for it as something unfulfilled, as, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "e.g.,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " he prays for the coming of God’s kingdom.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "In the insertion of this brief doxology the mind of the Apostle obeys an involuntary impulse of reverential awe. For a similar ascription in the same parenthetic form, comp. Romans 9:5.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "In the insertion of this brief doxology the mind of the Apostle obeys an involuntary impulse of reverential awe. For a similar ascription in the same parenthetic form, comp. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Romans 9:5",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ".",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "For ever and ever.—Literally, for ages of ages, a Hebraising expression for infinite time. Commonly, time was divided only into two great world-periods; but the second is, as it were, multiplied indefinitely—“for all possible ages.”",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "For ever and ever.",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "—Literally, ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "ital",
            "text": "for ages of ages,",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": " a Hebraising expression for infinite time. Commonly, time was divided only into two great world-periods; but the second is, as it were, multiplied indefinitely—“for all possible ages.”",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
