  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 5.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To whom be glory for ever and ever",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Amen",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ῶ ἡ δόξα εἰς τοὺς αἰῶνας τῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "αἰώνων Ἀμήν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This doxology is not introduced as merely a reverential closing up of the greeting, before the writer hastens on to the subsequent words of rebuke. It is rather an indignant tender of homage to the Most High, flashing forth from a loyal, filial heart; confronting and seeking, so far as it thus may, to redress the wrong done to \"our God and Father\" by the Judaizing spirit uprearing itself among the Galatians. It is similar in tone to the indignant doxology in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 1:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This view of its origin explains the fact that, as connected with a greeting, such doxology is found only in this of all St. Paul's Epistles. The indignation which pervades the tone of the whole passage favours the suppletion of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἔστω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather than of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐστίν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Perhaps, indeed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἔστω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is in general the more natural suppletion. In ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 4:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐστὶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is added by the writer, we have not so much a direct  ascription of praise as an affirmation that to God belongs or is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "due",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the glory of our performing our several duties with reference to this end. In like manner in the (most probably interpolated) doxology at the close of the Lord's prayer in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 6:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"For thine is the kingdom,\" etc., the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "ascription",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of praise is not so much expressed as implied. Viewed in themselves, the words simply state the truth which constitutes the ground for our addressing to \"our Father\" our praises and our petitions. The article is most commonly prefixed to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δόξα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in such ascriptions of praise, whether ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δόξα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " stands alone, as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 11:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 16:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 3:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Philippians 4:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hebrews 13:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Peter 3:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; or in conjunction with other nouns, as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Peter 4:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 1:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 7:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". It is wanting in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 2:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 19:38",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 1:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jude 1:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". When the article is added it marks the noun as expressing its notion viewed absolutely, in its entirety or universality: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "q.d.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"Whatever glory is to be ascribed anywhere, be it ascribed to him.\" Thus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἡ δόξα",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is equivalent to \"all glory.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "For ever and ever",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; literally, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "into the aions of the aions",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; apparently a form of expression adopted to denote intensification or superlativeness, like \"holy of holies\" (cf. Winer, 'Gram. N. T.,' § 36, 2). It is used where ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "especial",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " intensity is wished to be added to the notion of long undetermined duration; as ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 14:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 15:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 22:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. The same notion is expressed, only with not the same passionate earnestness, by the phrase, \"into the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "aions",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 1:33",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 1:25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 9:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 11:36",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; and by \"into the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "aion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",\" in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 21:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 6:51, 58",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. Possibly there is a reference of contrast to\" this present ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "aidn\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of ver. 4. This, however, is doubtful; for in ver. 4 ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "aion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " points to a particular condition of affairs subsisting in this ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "aion",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " rather than to a mere mode of duration, which latter is alone in view here. The like observation applies to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ephesians 2:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " compared with ver. 7. Galatians 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
